  "summary": "During the inquest, the coroner questions David Hunter regarding his whereabouts on Tuesday evening. When presented with a golden lighter found near the body, Hunter admits the item is his but claims he lost it on Friday morning. Mr. Guyson suggests the coroner might have inadvertently left his own lighter at the scene on Saturday, but the inquiry proceeds.\n\nCaptain George Douglas Potter, a former member of the Royal African Rifles, testifies that the deceased is his friend, Robert André. However, Rosaline Crowd (Mrs. Gordon-Claude) testifies that she does not know the body and insists the man is not her husband, Robert André. Despite her denial, the jury returns a verdict of premeditated murder against David Hunter.\n\nFollowing the inquest, Superintendent Spence, the county police chief, and Hercule Poirot meet to discuss the case. The police chief notes that André had previously planned to fake his death using the alias Enoch Yates. Spence expresses concern regarding the lack of concrete evidence, noting that the deserted nature of the English countryside makes finding witnesses difficult. He reveals that the primary evidence against Hunter is the golden lighter found under the body, though it lacks fingerprints. Additionally, the deceased's watch stopped at 9:10, which aligns with testimony that André was expecting a client. Spence concludes that the only individuals with a motive are David Hunter or his sister.",
